                        <bindingDesc>
                          <binding contemporary="true" xml:id="binding">
                            <decoNote xml:id="b1">
                              Ethiopic bookbinding with plain wooden boards.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="bindingMaterial">
                           <material key="wood"/>
                        </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b3" type="Boards">
                              The boards are carved from a light brown wood. The outer surface shows the signs of the instrument used for carving.
                              They have external bevels.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b6" type="SewingStations">3</decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b7">
                              The sewing is too damaged to identify the pattern. The codex was sewn on on three sewing stations.
                              In the last quire are visibile 6 ends of threads so three threads has been used for the sewing.
                              The system of board attachment is different from the typical one.
                              On the boards, for each sewing station, there are three holes in a line, parallel to the inner border, and one hole in the inner edge.
                              From the inner surface of the board the thread enters in the external two holes and then it converge in the middle hole.
                              From the middle hole, through a channel, it exits from the inner edge of the board.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b9" type="Spine">
                              Small holes are present close to the head and tail of the quires, prabably remains of the tackets.
                              Quire 5 has a red thread passing through the hole close to the head, securing the joint between the bifolios.
                            </decoNote>
                          </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
